library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(plotly)
*Reading the data*
file_path="/Users/Seval/Desktop/Musk1.csv"
musk = read.csv(file_path, header = FALSE)
*PCA analysis of the data by standardizing the data.*
musk_rev <-musk[,-c(1,2)] #removing the first two columns because they are not going to bu used in PCA analysis
pca_musk = prcomp(musk_rev, scale. = TRUE, center = TRUE)
summary(pca_musk)
variance_musk <- pca_musk$sdev^2 #Variance
var_exp_musk=100 * variance_musk / sum(variance_musk) #  percentage variation explained

text/plain: Plot with title “Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained”

source:
plot(cumsum(var_exp_musk), main = "Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained", xlab = "Principal Component",
              ylab = "Proportion",
              type = "b")

**As we can see, the first 3 components cover 52% of the variance and the first 12 components cover the 80% variance of the data. According to the plot above, it is not necessary to use more than 50 variables since the remanining variables does not contribute to the explained variable significantly.**
We can plot reduced dimensions on the following figures in which instances are color-coded with their bag labels.
pca_musk_3 = pca_musk$x[,1:3]
head(pca_musk_3)

inst_labels = as.factor(musk$V1)
pca_musk_3.df=as.data.frame(pca_musk_3)
pca_musk_3.df %>% 
    ggplot(aes(PC1, PC2, col = inst_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(col = "bag labels")

pca_musk_3.df %>% 
    ggplot(aes(PC2, PC3, col = inst_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(col = "bag labels")

pca_musk_3.df %>% 
    ggplot(aes(PC1, PC3, col = inst_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(col = "bag labels")

**In the plots given above, the first 3 component is plotted and we couldn't obtain a significant distinction. Therefore, we can conclude that assumption of the instance labels’ being as the same as bag labels is not an efficient solution.**
*Applying MDS after scaling the data.*

musk_rev_mat=as.matrix(musk_rev)
scaled_musk_rev_mat=scale(musk_rev_mat)
dist_mat=dist(scaled_musk_rev_mat)
mds_musk_3=as.data.frame(cmdscale(dist_mat, k=3))

mds_musk_3 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = mds_musk_3[,1], y = mds_musk_3[,2], col = inst_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Coordinate 1", y = "Coordinate 2", col = "bag labels")

mds_musk_3 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = mds_musk_3[,2], y = mds_musk_3[,3], col = inst_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Coordinate 2", y = "Coordinate 3", col = "bag labels")

mds_musk_3 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = mds_musk_3[,1], y = mds_musk_3[,3], col = inst_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Coordinate 1", y = "Coordinate 3", col = "bag labels")

**As we observed in the PCA case, we still can not obtain a significant distinction. Therefore, we can conclude that assumption of the instance labels’ being as the same as bag labels is not an efficient solution for MDS, too.**
**Part B**
*Taking the average of the instance features so that the bag is represented by the center of its instances.*

source:
musk_mean = musk %>% group_by(V2) %>%
  summarise_all(funs(mean)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-(V1:V2))

bag_labels = musk %>%
  group_by(V2) %>%
  summarise(V1 = head(V1,1))
*Applying PCA*

bag_labels = as.factor(bag_labels$V1)

pca_centered = prcomp(musk_mean, scale. = TRUE, center = TRUE)
pca_centered_3 = pca_centered$x[,1:3]
pca_centered_3.df=as.data.frame(pca_centered_3)

ggplot(pca_centered_3.df, aes(PC1, PC2, col = bag_labels))  +
  geom_point() +
  labs(col = "class")

ggplot(pca_centered_3.df, aes(PC2, PC3, col = bag_labels))  +
  geom_point() +
  labs(col = "class")

ggplot(pca_centered_3.df, aes(PC1, PC3, col = bag_labels))  +
  geom_point() +
  labs(col = "class")
**Still we don't have a significant separation. Therefore, we can conclude that averaging the instance features is not an efficient solution.**
variance_musk_centered <- pca_centered$sdev^2 #Variance
var_exp_musk_centered=100 * variance_musk_centered / sum(variance_musk_centered) #  percentage variation explained

text/plain: Plot with title “Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained”

source:
plot(cumsum(var_exp_musk_centered), main = "Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained", xlab = "Principal Component",
              ylab = "Proportion",
              type = "b")
summary(pca_centered)
**However, we can explain a higher amount of variation in the data in this way. We can explain 75% of the variance with first 5 component and 80% of the variance with first 6 component.**
*Applying MDS on the data after scaling.*

musk_scaled_centered = musk_mean %>%
  as.matrix() %>% 
  scale()

dist_mat_centered = dist(musk_scaled_centered)
mds_centered = cmdscale(dist_mat_centered, k=3)

mds_centered %>% as.data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(mds_centered[,1], mds_centered[,2], col = bag_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Coordinate 1", y = "Coordinate 2", col = "class")

mds_centered %>% as.data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(mds_centered[,2], mds_centered[,3], col = bag_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Coordinate 2", y = "Coordinate 3", col = "class")

mds_centered %>% as.data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(mds_centered[,1], mds_centered[,3], col = bag_labels)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Coordinate 1", y = "Coordinate 3", col = "class")
**We can observe the same situation as in the case of PCA. It is not a good transformation approach for classifying bags.**
**Part C**

We can represent each bag with the median of the instances. In this way we don't need to make extra calculations. Also, since choosing median has an advantage of getting rid of the outliers, it might give better results.
# Task 2
Here, the aim is to compress images using PCA.
*Necessary libraries*
library(jpeg)
library(grid)
*Loading the image*

image_path="/Users/Seval/Desktop/Seval_256.jpg"
image<-readJPEG(image_path)
image.df <- as.data.frame(image)
image.df
*Displaying the image*

r <- image[,,1]
g <- image[,,2]
b <- image[,,3]

col <- rgb(r, g, b)
dim(col) <- dim(r)
grid.raster(col, interpolate=FALSE)
*Adding noise*

r_noise <- runif(dim(r)[1]*dim(r)[2], min(r), 0.1*max(r))
r_noise_matrix=matrix(r_noise,dim(r)[1],dim(r)[2]) 

g_noise <- runif(dim(g)[1]*dim(g)[2], min(g), 0.1*max(g))
g_noise_matrix=matrix(g_noise,dim(g)[1],dim(g)[2]) 

b_noise <- runif(dim(b)[1]*dim(b)[2], min(b), 0.1*max(b))
b_noise_matrix=matrix(b_noise,dim(b)[1],dim(b)[2]) 

r_new <- r + r_noise_matrix 
g_new <- g + g_noise_matrix 
b_new <- b + b_noise_matrix
*Noise added image*

col2 <- rgb(r_new,g_new,b_new)
dim(col2) <- dim(r_new)
grid.raster(col2, interpolate=FALSE)
*Red channel*

col3 <- rgb(r_new,0,0)
dim(col3) <- dim(r_new)
grid.raster(col3, interpolate=FALSE)
*Green channel*

col4 <- rgb(0,g_new,0)
dim(col4) <- dim(g_new)
grid.raster(col4, interpolate=FALSE)
*Blue channel*

col5 <- rgb(0,0,b_new)
dim(col5) <- dim(b_new)
grid.raster(col5, interpolate=FALSE)
*Greyscale noisy image*

grayscaled<-r_new+g_new+b_new
grayscaled <- grayscaled/max(grayscaled) #converting to greyscale
grid.raster(grayscaled, interpolate=FALSE)
*Extracting patches from the image*

patch_size=25
number_of_patches=(256+1-patch_size)^2
number_of_patches

dim_of_patches=(patch_size)^2
patch<-array(0, dim=c(dim_of_patches, number_of_patches))
m=0
*Applying PCA to this data matrix of patches*

patchdt=as.data.frame(patch)
pca_image = prcomp(patchdt, scale.=TRUE, center=TRUE) 
summary(pca_image)
variance <- pca_image$sdev^2 #Variance
var_exp=100 * variance / sum(variance) #  percentage variation explained

text/plain: Plot with title “Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained”

source:
plot(cumsum(var_exp), main = "Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained", xlab = "Principal Component",
              ylab = "Proportion",
              type = "b")

**As we can see, the first 3 components cover 50% of the variance and the first 5 components cover the 60% variance of the data.  According to the plot above, it is not necessary to use more than 100 variables since the remanining variables does not contribute to the explained variable significantly.**
*Using only the first component PC1*

pca_comp<-pca_image$rotation
pca_comp1 <- matrix(pca_comp[,1], 232,232, byrow=T) #use only the first component PC1
pca_comp1_rev<-(pca_comp1-min(pca_comp1))/(max(pca_comp1)-min(pca_comp1))
grid.raster(pca_comp1_rev,interpolate=FALSE)
